llectually adventurous, politically engaged study applies borderlands and diaspora theory to Chicano cultural practices in a way that permanently changes our understanding of both the Chicano experience and the meaning of cultural theory. Defying national (and nationalistic) paradigms of culture, Saldívar argues that the culture of the borderlands is trans-national, constituting a social space in which new relations, hybrid cultures, and multi-voiced aesthetics are negotiated.Saldívar's critical readings treat culture as a social force and reveal the presence of social contexts within cultural texts. Border Matters maps out a new terrain for the study of culture, reshaping the way we understand migration, national identity, and intellectual inquiry itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aBiculturalismzMexican-American Border Region. 0aMexican American artszMexican-American Border Region. 0aPopular culturezMexican-American Border Region. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aamerican cultural studies.  aamerican nationalism.  aamerican popular culture.  aarturo islas.  aborderlands.  acarmen lomas garza.  achicanas.  achicano culture.  achicanos.  acomparative intercultural studies.  acultural studies.  acultural theory.  adecolonialization.  adiaspora theory.  aethnography.  aexpression.  ahybrids culture.  aintellectual inquiry.  ala frontera.  amigration.  anational identity.  arepresentation.  asocial context.  asocial force.  asocial space.  asociology.  atransnational.  atravel writing.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz97805202